SIMPLE: requiem
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Requiem
<hw>Re"qui*em</hw> <pr>(r?"kw?-?m;277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Acc. of
L. <ets>requies</ets> rest, the first words of the Mass being
⟦ldquo⟧<ets>Requiem</ets> aeternam dona eis, Domine,⟦rdquo⟧ give eternal
rest to them, O lord; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re + <ets>quies</ets> quiet.
See <er>Quiet</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, and cf. <er>Requin</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(R.C.Ch.)</fld> <def>A mass said or sung for the repose
of a departed soul.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We should profane the service of the dead⟦br⟧
To sing a <qex>requiem</qex> and such rest to her⟦br⟧
As to peace-parted souls.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any grand musical composition, performed in honor of
a deceased person.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Rest; quiet; peace.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Else had I an eternal <qex>requiem</qex> kept,⟦br⟧
And in the arms of peace forever slept.</q>
<rj><qau>Sandys.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Requietory</ent>⟦br⟧
